<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">MEASUREMENTS. Total body length 1.7, carapace width 0.7. Distance PME-PME 50 µm, diameter PME 65 µm, distance PME-ALE 55 µm, distance AME-AME 10 µm, diameter AME 20 µm. Sternum width/length: 0.50/ 0.35. Leg 1: 9.2 (2.2 + 0.2 + 2.5 + 3.5 + 0.8), tibia 2: 1.3, tibia 3: 0.9, tibia 4: 1.2; tibia 1 L/d: 39. Femora 1–4 width (at half length): 0.15, 0.17, 0.18, 0.17.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">
<collectionCode box="[199,278,476,500]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">COLOR</collectionCode>
(in ethanol). Prosoma and legs pale ochre-yellow, with very indistinct darker rings on legs; abdomen pale gray, not yellowish in heart area, slightly darker in front of gonopore, without darker area in front of spinnerets.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">
<collectionCode box="[199,264,584,607]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">BODY</collectionCode>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation box="[445,544,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURES665–676" captionStartId="150.[151,264,1890,1912]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,550,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@150.[151,1436,550,1868]" captionTargetPageId="150" captionText="FIGURES665–676. Live specimens,Carapoia agilis group andunplaced species.665–666.C. exiguasp.n., male and female from Morro de Pedra. 667–669. C. djavani sp. n., males from Pedra Talhada and Usina Serra Grande, female from Murici. 670–672. C. agilis sp. n., males from Saltinho and near Bonito, female from near Bonito. 673–674. C. maculata sp. n., male and female from Morro de Pedra.675–676.C. bispina sp. n., male and female from near Bonito." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202681/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Fig. 665</figureCitation>
; ocular area barely raised; carapace with very deep median furrow, carapace humps high; clypeus unmodified; sternum unmodified.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">
CHELICERAE. As in 
<figureCitation box="[421,517,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURES677–682" captionStartId="151.[151,264,1766,1788]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@151.[151,1436,193,1745]" captionTargetPageId="151" captionText="FIGURES677–682. Carapoia exigua sp. n. (♂: ZFMK Ar 19291; ♀: UFMG 21557).677–678.Left male palp, prolateral and retrolateral views. 679. Left procursus, dorsal view. 680. Male chelicerae, frontal view. 681. Epigynum, ventral view. 682. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view.Scale lines:0.3 (677–678), 0.2 (679–682)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202683/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Fig. 680</figureCitation>
, with two pairs of small frontal apophyses, apparently provided with one modified hair each.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">
<collectionCode box="[199,268,728,751]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">PALPS</collectionCode>
. As in 
<figureCitation box="[359,518,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURES677–682" captionStartId="151.[151,264,1766,1788]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@151.[151,1436,193,1745]" captionTargetPageId="151" captionText="FIGURES677–682. Carapoia exigua sp. n. (♂: ZFMK Ar 19291; ♀: UFMG 21557).677–678.Left male palp, prolateral and retrolateral views. 679. Left procursus, dorsal view. 680. Male chelicerae, frontal view. 681. Epigynum, ventral view. 682. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view.Scale lines:0.3 (677–678), 0.2 (679–682)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202683/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Figs 677–678</figureCitation>
; coxa with small retrolateral apophysis; trochanter barely modified; femur with large retrolatero-ventral process proximally, small dorsal hump, distally widening; procursus proximally arising from widened part of tarsus, very simple, distally with distinctive sclerotized and membranous elements (subdistal prolateral branch; 
<figureCitation box="[357,455,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURES677–682" captionStartId="151.[151,264,1766,1788]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@151.[151,1436,193,1745]" captionTargetPageId="151" captionText="FIGURES677–682. Carapoia exigua sp. n. (♂: ZFMK Ar 19291; ♀: UFMG 21557).677–678.Left male palp, prolateral and retrolateral views. 679. Left procursus, dorsal view. 680. Male chelicerae, frontal view. 681. Epigynum, ventral view. 682. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view.Scale lines:0.3 (677–678), 0.2 (679–682)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202683/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Fig. 679</figureCitation>
); genital bulb with large mostly membranous process with prolateral pointed sclerite at tip and slender transparent process.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">
<collectionCode box="[199,258,909,932]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">LEGS</collectionCode>
. Densely covered with short hairs, without spines, without curved hairs, few vertical hairs; retrolateral trichobothrium on tibia 1 at 9%; prolateral trichobothrium present on tibia 1; tarsus 1 with ~15 pseudosegments, distally fairly distinct.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" box="[199,690,1015,1040]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,260,1015,1040]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Male</emphasis>
(variation). Tibia 
<quantity box="[464,507,1015,1040]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="152" pageNumber="153" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
other male: 2.3.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,293,1052,1077]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Female.</emphasis>
In general similar to male (
<figureCitation box="[604,703,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES665–676" captionStartId="150.[151,264,1890,1912]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,550,1868]" captionTargetId="figure@150.[151,1436,550,1868]" captionTargetPageId="150" captionText="FIGURES665–676. Live specimens,Carapoia agilis group andunplaced species.665–666.C. exiguasp.n., male and female from Morro de Pedra. 667–669. C. djavani sp. n., males from Pedra Talhada and Usina Serra Grande, female from Murici. 670–672. C. agilis sp. n., males from Saltinho and near Bonito, female from near Bonito. 673–674. C. maculata sp. n., male and female from Morro de Pedra.675–676.C. bispina sp. n., male and female from near Bonito." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202681/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Fig. 666</figureCitation>
). Tibia 
<quantity box="[786,829,1052,1077]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="152" pageNumber="153" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
three females: 1.8, 2.0, 2.0. Epigynum as in 
<figureCitation box="[1332,1431,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES677–682" captionStartId="151.[151,264,1766,1788]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@151.[151,1436,193,1745]" captionTargetPageId="151" captionText="FIGURES677–682. Carapoia exigua sp. n. (♂: ZFMK Ar 19291; ♀: UFMG 21557).677–678.Left male palp, prolateral and retrolateral views. 679. Left procursus, dorsal view. 680. Male chelicerae, frontal view. 681. Epigynum, ventral view. 682. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view.Scale lines:0.3 (677–678), 0.2 (679–682)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202683/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Figs 681</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[151,195,1088,1112]" captionStart="FIGURES 711–720" captionStartId="160.[151,264,1473,1495]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,409,1452]" captionTargetId="figure@160.[151,1436,409,1452]" captionTargetPageId="160" captionText="FIGURES 711–720. Female epigyna in ventral views and cleared female genitalia in dorsal views, Carapoia agilis group and unplaced species. 711–712. Carapoia exigua sp. n., from Morro de Pedra (UFMG 21557). 713–714. C. djavani sp. n., from Pedra Talhada (ZFMK Ar 19292). 715–716. C. agilis sp. n., from near Bonito (ZFMK Ar 19295). 717, 720. C. bispina sp. n., from near Bonito (ZFMK Ar 19300). 718–719.C. maculata sp. n., from Morro de Pedra (ZFMK Ar 19299)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202693/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">711</figureCitation>
; anterior plate simple trapezoidal, weakly protruding; with pair of diverging sclerites in membrane behind anterior plate; without posterior plate. Internal genitalia as in 
<figureCitation box="[838,939,1124,1149]" captionStart="FIGURES677–682" captionStartId="151.[151,264,1766,1788]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1731]" captionTargetId="figure@151.[151,1436,193,1745]" captionTargetPageId="151" captionText="FIGURES677–682. Carapoia exigua sp. n. (♂: ZFMK Ar 19291; ♀: UFMG 21557).677–678.Left male palp, prolateral and retrolateral views. 679. Left procursus, dorsal view. 680. Male chelicerae, frontal view. 681. Epigynum, ventral view. 682. Cleared female genitalia, dorsal view.Scale lines:0.3 (677–678), 0.2 (679–682)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202683/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Figs 682</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[950,995,1124,1148]" captionStart="FIGURES 711–720" captionStartId="160.[151,264,1473,1495]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,409,1452]" captionTargetId="figure@160.[151,1436,409,1452]" captionTargetPageId="160" captionText="FIGURES 711–720. Female epigyna in ventral views and cleared female genitalia in dorsal views, Carapoia agilis group and unplaced species. 711–712. Carapoia exigua sp. n., from Morro de Pedra (UFMG 21557). 713–714. C. djavani sp. n., from Pedra Talhada (ZFMK Ar 19292). 715–716. C. agilis sp. n., from near Bonito (ZFMK Ar 19295). 717, 720. C. bispina sp. n., from near Bonito (ZFMK Ar 19300). 718–719.C. maculata sp. n., from Morro de Pedra (ZFMK Ar 19299)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202693/files/figure.png" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">712</figureCitation>
, with distinctively shaped pore-plates.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="152.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,391,1159,1184]" pageId="152" pageNumber="153">Natural history.</emphasis>
Spiders were found running rapidly on the ground. Sometimes they seemed to make small jumps and then they stopped immediately, making them essentially invisible.
</paragraph>
